diff --git a/ROOT-SECURITY-RELEASE.md b/ROOT-SECURITY-RELEASE.md
new file mode 100644
index 000000000..aabbcc002
--- /dev/null
+++ b/ROOT-SECURITY-RELEASE.md
@@ -0,0 +1,79 @@
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------
+
+## Why CVE-2024-28757 Is a False Positive for **libexpat2 2.2.10-2+deb11u7** on Debian Bullseye
+
+## Overview: What Is **libexpat2**?
+
+**libexpat2** is a stream-oriented XML parser library written in C. It is one of the most widely used XML parsers in the Linux ecosystem and is embedded or linked by many critical packages including Python, Apache HTTP Server, Git, CMake, D-Bus, and others.
+
+The **libexpat2** library provides:
+- **Stream-based XML parsing**: SAX-style event-driven parsing without loading the entire document into memory
+- **DTD processing**: Support for Document Type Definitions including external entity resolution
+- **Namespace support**: XML namespace-aware parsing capabilities
+- **Configurable security**: APIs to control entity expansion limits and parser behavior
+
+**libexpat2** is a core dependency present in virtually all Linux distributions.
+
+## Why This Vulnerability Doesn't Affect 2.2.10-2+deb11u7
+
+Security scanning tools like **Trivy**, **Grype**, and others may flag CVE-2024-28757 on `libexpat2` even when:
+
+- The CVE targets a **bypass of the billion laughs attack protection** in the `accountingGetCurrentAmplification` function
+- This protection mechanism was **introduced in libexpat 2.4.0** as a fix for CVE-2013-0340
+- Debian Bullseye ships **libexpat2 2.2.10**, which **predates 2.4.0** — the `accountingGetCurrentAmplification` function and the entire amplification accounting subsystem **do not exist** in this version
+- The Debian Security Tracker marks this CVE as urgency **"unimportant"** with no DSA issued
+- Debian has **not backported** the billion laughs protection (CVE-2013-0340 fix) to bullseye, so the bypass vulnerability cannot exist
+
+These factors cause scanners to **misidentify this CVE as present**, leading to **false positives** for Debian Bullseye.
+
+---
+## 📌 CVE-2024-28757 – False Positive in libexpat2 2.2.10-2+deb11u7
+
+**Component:** `accountingGetCurrentAmplification` function in `xmlparse.c`
+**Issue:** When using isolated external parsers (created via `XML_ExternalEntityParserCreate`), `countBytesDirect` is 0 and the amplification function returns `1.0f` instead of calculating the actual amplification ratio. This allows billion laughs attacks to bypass the protection mechanism.
+**Impact:** Denial of Service via XML Entity Expansion (CVSS 3.1: 7.5 HIGH) — but only in versions that contain the protection code (2.4.0 through 2.6.1)
+
+---
+
+## 🔍 Vulnerability Overview
+
+- **Component impacted:** `accountingGetCurrentAmplification` in `expat/lib/xmlparse.c` — billion laughs amplification tracking
+- **Nature of issue:** When `countBytesDirect` is 0 (isolated external parser), the function returned `1.0f` indicating no amplification, bypassing billion laughs detection
+- **Fix:** Replace the `1.0f` fallback with a calculation using an assumed minimum direct input of 22 bytes (the length of `<!ENTITY a SYSTEM 'b'>`)
+- **Severity:** HIGH (CVSS 3.1: 7.5) — AV:N/AC:L/PR:N/UI:N/S:U/C:N/I:N/A:H
+- **Attack vector:** Network — remote attacker sends crafted XML with recursive entity definitions to an application using isolated external parsers
+
+---
+
+## ✅ libexpat2 2.2.10-2+deb11u7 – Why This is a False Positive
+
+- **Billion laughs protection was added in libexpat 2.4.0** — Debian Bullseye ships 2.2.10, which is **1.5 major versions earlier**
+- **The function `accountingGetCurrentAmplification` does not exist in 2.2.10** — the entire amplification accounting subsystem (`m_accounting.countBytesDirect`, `m_accounting.countBytesIndirect`) was introduced in 2.4.0
+- **No protection to bypass** — CVE-2024-28757 is a bypass of a defense mechanism that was never present in 2.2.10
+- **Debian never backported CVE-2013-0340 fix** — the billion laughs protection was not backported to bullseye, confirming the vulnerable code path does not exist
+- **Debian Security Tracker urgency is "unimportant"** — no DSA issued; notes reference that "Expat provides API to mitigate expansion attacks, ultimately under control of the app using Expat"
+- **Scanner false positive** — triggered by generic version-range matching (`<= 2.6.1`) without validating that the vulnerable code path (amplification accounting) does not exist in 2.2.10
+
+---
+
+## ⚠️ Why You Don't Need to Fix It
+
+- **No vulnerable code present in 2.2.10** — the `accountingGetCurrentAmplification` function and billion laughs accounting were added in 2.4.0, not present in this version
+- **Cannot bypass what doesn't exist** — CVE-2024-28757 is a bypass of amplification detection; 2.2.10 has no amplification detection to bypass
+- **Upstream fix commit modifies code absent from 2.2.10** — commit `1d50b80` changes `accountingGetCurrentAmplification` which does not exist in the 2.2.10 source tree
+- **No security impact** on Debian Bullseye systems from this specific CVE
+- **False positive from scanners** due to imprecise CVE version-range matching on the `libexpat2` package name without code-level validation of whether the billion laughs accounting subsystem is present
+
+---
+
+## 🔗 References
+
+- [**NVD Entry – CVE-2024-28757**](https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/CVE-2024-28757)
+- [**Debian Security Tracker – CVE-2024-28757**](https://security-tracker.debian.org/tracker/CVE-2024-28757)
+- [**Upstream fix commit – 1d50b80**](https://github.com/libexpat/libexpat/commit/1d50b80cf31de87750103656f6eb693746854aa8)
+- [**GitHub PR #842 – Prevent billion laughs in isolated external parser**](https://github.com/libexpat/libexpat/pull/842)
+- [**GitHub Issue #839 – Billion laughs with external parser**](https://github.com/libexpat/libexpat/issues/839)
+- [**CVE-2013-0340 – Original billion laughs fix (added in 2.4.0)**](https://blog.hartwork.org/posts/cve-2013-0340-billion-laughs-fixed-in-expat-2-4-0/)
+
